specialised environment for sperm development","Prevents testosterone from entering the bloodstream","Regulates testicular temperature","Facilitates immune cell migration","Controls blood flow to the seminiferous tubules"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Especialised environment\u003C/strong\u003E created by the blood-testis barrier is essential for proper spermatogenesis. The barrier forms tight junctions between adjacent Sertoli cells, controlling the composition of seminiferous tubule fluid and protecting developing sperm cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe barrier does not \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevent testosterone\u003C/strong\u003E movement, as testosterone needs to reach developing sperm cells. It also does not \u003Cstrong\u003Eregulate temperature\u003C/strong\u003E, which is controlled by the cremasteric muscle and testicular blood vessels. The barrier actually prevents \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmune cell migration\u003C/strong\u003E, not facilitates it, protecting developing sperm cells from immune recognition. It does not \u003Cstrong\u003Econtrol blood flow\u003C/strong\u003E, which is regulated by testicular vasculature.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The blood-testis barrier creates a specialised microenvironment necessary for spermatogenesis by controlling fluid composition within seminiferous tubules","The blood-testis barrier prevents immune cells from attacking developing sperm cells which would otherwise be recognised as foreign"],"references":["Cheng CY, Mruk DD. The blood-testis barrier and its implications for male contraception. Pharmacol Rev. 2012 Jan;64(1):16-64. doi: 10.1124/pr.110.002790. Epub 2011 Oct 28. PMID: 22039149; PMCID: PMC3250082.","Holstein AF, Schulze W, Davidoff M. Understanding spermatogenesis is a prerequisite for treatment. Reprod Biol Endocrinol. 2003 Nov 14;1:107. doi: 10.1186/1477-7827-1-107. PMID: 14617369; PMCID: PMC293421","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56990"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15787"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56990","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56990"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T18:30:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T18:32:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8478"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71481"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4934"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Reproductive Sy